      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Thorium is a radioactive metal, soft, malleable, silvery-white in colour. Freshly cut thorium is lustrous, but on contact with air develops a grey coating of thorium oxide – Th</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. At room temperature thorium gradually reacts with water to form thorium hydroxide </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> – Th(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">4</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">The element dissolves in acids to produce salts. Thorium is the first element in a natural radioactive decay series - the thorium series. The longest-lived isotope is </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">232</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Th with a half-life of </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">1.4 · </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">10</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">10</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> years (14 billion years) The element was discovered in 1828 by Jöns Jacob Berzelius. It was named after Thor, the Norse god of thunder. Thorium is an actinide element.</text>
